---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
---

<MainLayout title="Bigger Picture">
    <section class="space-y-10">
        <div class="max-w-4xl">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-indigo-600 mb-3">
                Rand Water Project Challenge
            </p>
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 mb-4">
                Looking at the Bigger Picture
            </h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-600">
                The vandalism of Rand Water assets is not only a physical security issue. It affects service delivery,
                business continuity, costs, trust, and long-term sustainability. Understanding the wider context helps
                explain why this problem is urgent and why change is needed.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Why this problem matters</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-7">
                Vandals systematically damage water pumping stations, reservoirs, water meters, pipelines, and other critical
                components, resulting in major repair costs and disruptions to water supply services. In some cases, stolen
                water meters and reconstruction costs run into millions of rand. The problem is also linked to organized
                criminal activity, including so-called “water mafias,” where sabotage is used to create opportunities for
                profitable water supply or tanker contracts.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-7 mt-4">
                This means the challenge is bigger than asset protection: it reflects corruption, crime, inequality, and weak
                enforcement. A practical solution must therefore reduce the value of stolen components, discourage vandalism,
                and support reliable water delivery to communities.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">PESTEL Analysis</h2>

            <div class="grid gap-6">
                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Political</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>Awareness campaigns against vandalism exist, but they are not sufficient on their own.</li>
                        <li>Government failure to provide equality can fuel unrest and vandalism.</li>
                        <li>Lack of cooperation between agencies weakens the response to infrastructure crime.</li>
                        <li>There is insufficient political will and weak policing of critical infrastructure.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>

                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Economic</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>Unemployment is above 30%, which increases pressure on households and communities.</li>
                        <li>Youth unemployment is above 50%, creating social and economic instability.</li>
                        <li>South Africa has extreme income inequality and one of the highest Gini coefficients in the world.</li>
                        <li>Millions of South Africans live in poverty, which can intensify crime and opportunistic vandalism.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>

                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Social</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>South Africa experiences a high crime rate.</li>
                        <li>Poor delivery of electricity, water, and road maintenance affects economic stability and security.</li>
                        <li>Substance abuse is widespread and can contribute to destructive behaviour.</li>
                        <li>Protest culture and social frustration can sometimes lead to sabotage and vandalism.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>

                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Technological</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>South Africa is a leader in Africa’s digital economy.</li>
                        <li>More than 75% of households have internet access.</li>
                        <li>About 97% of households have at least one mobile phone.</li>
                        <li>The state is increasingly integrating technology into public services to improve efficiency and service delivery.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>

                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Environmental</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>Climate change is increasing water-related risks, including floods and droughts.</li>
                        <li>South Africa faces major pressure from rainfall extremes and climate-related disasters.</li>
                        <li>There is not enough investment in water infrastructure to fully meet demand.</li>
                        <li>Only a small percentage of wastewater is recycled, which increases sustainability concerns.</li>
                        <li>The project aligns with SDG 6: clean water and sanitation for all.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>

                <article class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Legal</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-slate-700">
                        <li>South Africa has a well-developed legal framework for crimes such as malicious injury to property and arson.</li>
                        <li>Legal liability can apply where damage is intentional or foreseeable.</li>
                        <li>However, enforcement is often limited by weak resources and the difficulty of dealing with smaller crime claims.</li>
                    </ul>
                </article>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-indigo-200 bg-indigo-50 p-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Conclusion</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-7">
                Rand Water’s vandalism problem sits at the intersection of crime, inequality, weak enforcement, and infrastructure
                pressure. The bigger picture shows that a solution must be practical, affordable, and designed to reduce the
                incentive to steal critical components. This is why replacing metal parts with cheaper materials is a strong first
                alternative: it directly reduces theft value while supporting more resilient water service delivery.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>
</MainLayout>